 {"id":"wa-3d14m","title":"Phase 2: Replace tokio sync primitives with asupersync","description":"# Phase 2: Replace tokio sync primitives

## Goal
Replace all tokio::sync primitives (Mutex, RwLock, Semaphore) with asupersync equivalents across the codebase.

## Scope
- tokio::sync::Mutex → asupersync::sync::Mutex (with guard obligation tracking)
- tokio::sync::RwLock → asupersync::sync::RwLock (with guard obligation tracking)
- tokio::sync::Semaphore/OwnedSemaphorePermit → asupersync::sync::Semaphore (with permit obligation)

## Key difference: Obligation tracking
asupersync sync primitives enforce that guards/permits are properly released. The obligation system uses LeakChecker and ObligationVar to catch forgotten guards at scope exit.

## Affected files (primary)
- crates/wa-core/src/pool.rs — Semaphore + Mutex for connection pooling (CRITICAL)
- crates/wa-core/src/runtime.rs — RwLock for shared state
- crates/wa-core/src/mcp.rs — Mutex for tool registration
- crates/wa-core/src/web.rs — Mutex/RwLock for request handling
- Multiple other modules using Arc<Mutex<T>> and Arc<RwLock<T>>

## Migration pattern
```rust
// Before (tokio)
use tokio::sync::Mutex;
let data = Arc::new(Mutex::new(value));
let guard = data.lock().await;

// After (asupersync)
use asupersync::sync::Mutex;
let data = Arc::new(Mutex::new(value));
let guard = data.lock(cx).await?;  // Note: takes cx, returns Outcome
```

## Acceptance criteria
- All tokio::sync::{Mutex, RwLock, Semaphore} replaced
- Guard obligations properly tracked
- Existing tests pass with new primitives
- No deadlock regressions

## Concurrency verification
- **Loom model checking**: Use Loom to model-check ALL replaced sync primitives. Specifically:
  - Mutex: verify mutual exclusion, no deadlocks under all thread interleavings
  - RwLock: verify readers-writer invariant (multiple readers OR single writer), no starvation
  - Semaphore: verify permit count invariant never goes negative, FIFO fairness under contention
  - Add `tests/loom_sync.rs` with `#[test]` functions wrapped in `loom::model(|| { ... })` for each primitive.

## Benchmark requirements
- **Criterion benchmarks**: Compare tokio vs asupersync performance for each replaced primitive. Add `benches/sync_primitives.rs` measuring:
  - Uncontended lock/unlock latency (Mutex, RwLock)
  - Contended lock/unlock with N=2,4,8 tasks
  - Semaphore acquire/release throughput
  - Guard obligation tracking overhead (should be negligible in release builds)
  - Include both `tokio` and `asupersync` benchmark groups for direct A/B comparison.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:48:16.744371Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-02-10T19:47:23.02984Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"wa-3d14m","depends_on_id":"wa-2lp7o","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:51:57.257002Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}"},{"issue_id":"wa-3d14m","depends_on_id":"wa-d0m4t","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:51:57.368732Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}"},{"issue_id":"wa-3d14m","depends_on_id":"wa-1j0ye","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:51:57.470058Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}"}]}
 {"id":"wa-3dfxb","title":"[EPIC] FrankenTerm Scripting Engine — Lua + WASM Dual Runtime","description":"# FrankenTerm Scripting Engine — Lua + WASM Dual Runtime

## Strategic Decision (2026-02-10)
After debate, we chose Option C: keep Lua AND add WASM via wasmtime. This gives us:
- **Backward compatibility** with existing WezTerm Lua configs (huge ecosystem)
- **Modern extensibility** via WASM (any language → .wasm → runs sandboxed)
- **Migration path**: Lua = legacy/quick scripting, WASM = serious extensions, over time WASM primary

## Why NOT the other options
- **Option A (Lua only)**: Keeps C build dep (mlua+LuaJIT), single language, no sandbox
- **Option B (WASM only)**: Breaks every existing WezTerm config, too disruptive
- **Option D (V8)**: +30MB binary, C++ dep, overkill for terminal emulator

## Architecture: ScriptingEngine trait
Both engines implement a common `ScriptingEngine` trait:
```rust
pub trait ScriptingEngine: Send + Sync {
    fn eval_config(&self, path: &Path) -> Result<TerminalConfig>;
    fn register_hook(&self, event: &str, handler: ExtensionHandler) -> Result<HookId>;
    fn fire_event(&self, event: &str, payload: &dyn ToDynamic) -> Result<Vec<Action>>;
    fn load_extension(&self, manifest: &ExtensionManifest) -> Result<ExtensionId>;
}
```

## Feature flags
- `lua` (default) — enables mlua/LuaJIT, wezterm.lua config compat
- `wasm` — enables wasmtime, WASM extension loading
- `scripting-all` — both lua + wasm (for development/testing)
- `no-lua` — compiles out all Lua paths (headless/minimal builds)

## WASM runtime choice: wasmtime
- **Rust-native** (Bytecode Alliance, same org as wasm-tools)
- ~5MB binary overhead (vs ~30MB for V8)
- Full WASI support (filesystem, env vars, stdio)
- Component Model support (structured types, not just i32)
- Used by Zellij for plugins — proven in terminal space

## Build time impact
- Lua only: ~36s clean (LuaJIT C compilation is single-threaded)
- WASM only: ~20s clean (wasmtime is pure Rust, parallelizes well)
- Both: ~40s clean (but most users only enable one)
- no-lua: ~15s clean (minimal build)

## Extension package format (.ftx)
FrankenTerm eXtension bundles: ZIP containing manifest.toml + *.wasm + assets.
Can also contain Lua scripts for backward compat.

## Phases
1. Make Lua optional (feature flags in config, mux, luahelper)
2. Define ScriptingEngine trait abstraction
3. Add wasmtime + WASI integration
4. Implement WasmEngine
5. Build extension system
6. Config format evolution (TOML + WASM evaluation)
7. Migration tooling + documentation

## Relationship to other work
- Depends on wa-2umk2 (in-tree source ownership — can modify config/mux crates)
- FrankenMux (wa-2dd4s) benefits from WASM plugin panes (like Zellij)
- Ghostty analysis (wa-3bja) may reveal additional extension points
- asupersync (wa-e34d9) provides the async runtime for WASM I/O","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-02-10T06:52:21.712816Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-02-10T07:31:22.850828Z","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"wa-3dfxb","depends_on_id":"wa-2umk2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-10T06:52:56.037582Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}"}]}
